              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google detects PBNs through technical footprints (shared IP addresses, hosting accounts, WHOIS data, analytics IDs), content patterns (thin content, unnatural outbound profiles, zero organic traffic), and link patterns (similar anchor text, high DA with no real traffic).</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What happens if Google catches a PBN?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google issues a manual action removing the money site from search results, or algorithmically devalues the PBN links so they pass no authority. Recovery requires a reconsideration request (2–4 weeks response time) and clean-up — with no guarantee of full recovery.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What are legitimate alternatives to PBNs?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Effective white-hat alternatives include digital PR and content marketing, guest posting on real editorial sites, broken link building, resource page outreach, HARO journalist responses, and original research projects. These require 1–6 months but produce defensible, long-term rankings.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

